post_text:
Fan protocol for the Upton/Sundance JVFB game on Monday.

All spectators will be screened when they enter the facility. No temperature checks.

Face covering are required if you can’t social distance other than when in family pods.

Face coverings are required when you use the restrooms at the football field.

All students must sit with their parents/adult.

No one will be allowed inside the fence other than the players, coaches, workers, officials and the band.

Band members must stay through halftime in the area designated for the band.

We apologize for the inconveniences that this causes but we are doing what we can for our athletes to have a season.

#NeverForget
It has been 19 years since that day that changed many of our lives and I like many of you can remember exactly where we were, what we were doing and how the day played out.
As memorials take place in New York, Washington D.C and Pennsylvania it behoves us all to take a moment today to remember all those who were at those ground zeros and lost their lives or risked their lives in an attempt to save their brothers and sisters.

post_text: With fall sports comes many great traditions and activities. With our students not coming back to campus until today we want to give our student leaders enough time to prepare for one of the best traditions/activities we have in the fall – Homecoming. Originally scheduled for Friday September 25 Homecoming will now be October 9 vs. Mitchell. As mentioned this will give our Student Council more time to prepare and the opportunity for the district to be in "Green" enabling more people come and enjoy all the traditional festivities. We will recognize our football seniors on September 25 against Huron.

post_text: With the district starting in Orange, we will be implementing the pass list protocol starting with tomorrow night’s volleyball game vs. STM. Reminder that this protocol allows for four (4) names to be placed on the pass list by each rostered player, manager and coach. The pass list protocol will be used until the district transitions back into the Green Phase. Activity tickets are able to be used by those individuals whose names are on the pass list. Coaches will be communicating with players and families to create the list. We understand that this is yet another change and we greatly appreciate your flexibility. We invite all fans to watch the contests on our NFHS network (West Gym Activities) and Black Hills TV (football) platforms. #ScooperSpirit #WeWantASeason

• Exit out the long hallway doors

post_text: Reality Stinks at times Today it was reported that an athlete who attends workout classes at Rapid Skills tested positive for Covid-19. After investigating it doesn’t appear that any of our athletes were exposed as it was a male, and the only record we have is females going to Rapid Skills. Thus, we have no exposures. This is a great example of why we need TOTAL OPEN AND HONEST COMMUNICATION between athletes and coaches here in Scooper State. We are not going to tell you that you can’t go somewhere, but we need to know so we can be proactive if something happens. Thank you for your continued help with this as we work through these trying times.

Meade School District
June 3 at 9:47 AM ·

Meade School District is pleased to announce that a generous donation has been received to pay off all student lunch balances at Piedmont Elementary School and Stagebarn Middle School.

A check in the amount of $2337.98 was received from Tim and Andrea Brady of Kumelos Design and Construction, Inc. of Piedmont, SD.

The donation paid off the lunch balances of 53 students in the Piedmont and Summerset areas, giving those families a fresh start for the coming school year.

Thank you so much, Bradys! You are school lunch heroes!

shared_text:
Meade School District
May 14 at 2:33 PM ·

**Edited to clarify: Children do NOT have to be Meade Schools Students to receive lunches. **
Our summer feeding program will begin on Thursday, May 21st at Sturgis Elementary. Hot lunches will be delivered curbside between 11 am and 12:30. All lunches are free of charge to every child up to the age of 18. Children do not have to be Meade Schools students to receive the lunches.

Also, we have received a generous grant from the BH Area Community Foundation and the Albert and LaVerne Elliot Fund that will allow us to serve parents as well! Parents will receive a meal along with their children until the funds run out.

Lunches will be served each weekday through at least July 31st. No lunches will be served on Memorial Day or on July 3rd.

This institution is an equal opportunity provider.

post_text: One of two special messages we would like to share today with our graduating seniors. #ClassOf2020 #ScooperSpirit
shared_text:
Senator John Thune
May 16 at 10:02 AM ·

I want you to know that I feel your pain and appreciate what you guys are having to go through. I know you won’t have the graduation you imagined, but in times like these, I believe adversity makes people stronger.

When I look back on school, I don’t remember the exams or papers or even my exact GPA. What I do remember is my friends, my teachers, my coaches, and the many lessons I learned.

Trust me, that’s what you’ll remember too.

Congratulations, class of 2020! Since you may not have a graduation speaker this year, allow me to share some of my thoughts.

The academic lockers at SBHS were cleaned out today, Wednesday, April 8, 2020. The items from the lockers were bagged and will be available for pick-up on Friday, April 10 from 9:00 am to 10:30 am. This would also be a good opportunity to pick up your student’s medication. Finally, if your student was in one of Sage’s fitness classes we ask that they please stop by and pick up their binder.
#WhoHatesCovid. #StaySafeStayAtHome

At her press briefing today, Gov. Noem asked that South Dakota schools remain closed for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year. That said, Meade 46-1 will continue with the flex learning options put into place over the last few weeks until the end of the regular school calendar upon approval by the School Board. The expectation from the Governor is that schools will continue to provide instruction to students and will stick to their original calendars for SY 2019-20 as much as possible.
In addition, Meade 46-1 will continue running the food program.

IMPORTANT INFORMATION FOR STURGIS BROWN HIGH SCHOOL PARENTS/GUARDIANS
Thank you for your participation in the survey and after reading the results, we are making some adjustments. We are instructing the teachers to include the parent/guardians to their weekly communication method to students on the weekly assignments. Currently every Sunday or Monday teachers communicate with students about their weekly assignments, now they will also include parent/guardians to that communication method.
We will begin hosting a Monday night announcements video, that we will put on OUR social media platforms to give parents and students additional information about what is going on. Please take a look.
We realize that some websites and educational apps are sometimes really slow. We believe it is because the whole country is online and using the same platforms. Please be patient while we are working on it.
Parents, if any phone numbers or emails need to be updated in Infinite Campus, please email Pam Vinson or call the school 347-2686 and leave a message.
text:
IMPORTANT INFORMATION FOR STURGIS BROWN HIGH SCHOOL PARENTS/GUARDIANS
Thank you for your participation in the survey and after reading the results, we are making some adjustments. We are instructing the teachers to include the parent/guardians to their weekly communication method to students on the weekly assignments. Currently every Sunday or Monday teachers communicate with students about their weekly assignments, now they will also include parent/guardians to that communication method.
We will begin hosting a Monday night announcements video, that we will put on OUR social media platforms to give parents and students additional information about what is going on. Please take a look.
We realize that some websites and educational apps are sometimes really slow. We believe it is because the whole country is online and using the same platforms. Please be patient while we are working on it.
Parents, if any phone numbers or emails need to be updated in Infinite Campus, please email Pam Vinson or call the school 347-2686 and leave a message.

Scooper State
March 19 at 10:43 AM ·

Sturgis Brown High School senior Ryan Conover will be featured as part of KEVN Black Hills FOX’s Rising Star of the West scholarship contest Wednesday March 25th on The SIX and on Black Hills FOX News at 9:00. Conover qualified for the contest by submitting a short video of herself to KEVN Black Hills FOX. Conover is one of the semi-finalists who will be seen through April 12th. Her one minute commentary will be aired and then placed on www.blackhillsfox.com for viewers to watch and rate. One competitor from each week will then advance to the final round in May. The winner from that group will receive a $4,000 college scholarship, with a total of $7,500 in scholarship money awarded from KEVN Black Hills FOX and Monument Health. Best of luck Ryan #ScooperProud

post_text:
Elementary School
Classroom Communication: Teachers will use individual preferential communication modes they have used throughout the year. Teachers need to be reaching out and be communicating with students/parents. If they aren't reaching them in one capacity, they are asked to try another. Teachers need to make sure kids/parents know the expectations for the day on what they have to complete. If they don't have internet or a device- alternative activities are given to replace the online activities. As students run out of worksheets (as some did packets), teachers may screenshot or send an attachment of expected activities through their communication style with parents. At this point, we are not requiring anything to be handed in until we return, but teachers are welcome to ask parents to screenshot some completed work to allow them to gauge for understanding and check for mastery.

With the announcement today that Meade Schools will be closed due to Covid19 (Coronavirus) Please review the follow about the activities in the Meade School District:
All school sponsored activities are in a moratorium and are not to hold group organized practices.
All activities scheduled for the week of March 16-20 are postponed
We understand the importance of activities to the educational experience we offer in the Meade School District and will do everything in our power to reschedule as many of those activities as we can while keeping our students safety in mind.
STAY HOME - STAY SAFE - MAKE GOOD CHOICES

post_text:
The Meade 46-1 school district will be closed next week in response to the Governors recommendation as a response the COVID 19 virus. We will use that time to do a deep clean and sanitize. The school administration and teachers have prepared instruction to be done virtually for our 5-12 students with their apple devices. Please help monitor the use of the Apple devices and make sure that when students come back to school, they bring the charger that came with the device. Our k-5 students will have work sent home with them.
The information on the COVID-19 virus changes hourly. One thing that continues to be a theme is elderly and those with a compromised immune system are the most susceptible to the virus.

All activities and practices have been cancelled. The library and the community center will be closed.

I will send more information home as it develops, however, best case scenario is that we are back in school on Monday March 23rd after the deep clean.
